          "body": "Verses 4-6 constitute the most detailed catalog of elite excess in the Hebrew prophets. Ivory beds (6:4) — the excavations at Samaria have unearthed ivories consistent with Amos's description (the Samaria Ivories, now in the British Museum). Lambs from the flock and calves from the stall (6:4) — the choicest animals, slaughtered for private consumption. Music improvised in the manner of David (6:5) — not to worship God but for personal entertainment. Wine from sacrificial bowls (6:6) — vessels consecrated for temple use now repurposed for banquet excess. The finest anointing oils (6:6). Every sense is gratified. But the climactic indictment is not any single luxury item: 'they have not grieved over the ruin of Joseph' (6:6). The word for 'ruin' (shever) means a breaking, a fracturing. The northern kingdom — Joseph — is fracturing socially, morally, covenantally; the people are being crushed under unjust economic arrangements (cf. 2:6-8; 4:1). And the elite, who could do something about it, have chosen feasting. The absence of grief is the sin. As Calvin observed, the prophets do not condemn wealth as such but the use of wealth to insulate oneself from the suffering of the community one is called to shepherd."
