          "title": "The divine oath — when God swears by Himself",
          "body": "Verse 8 is one of the most theologically weighted verses in Amos. 'The Lord God has sworn by Himself' — the Hebrew reads *benaphsho*, 'by His soul' or 'by Himself,' the same construction as Genesis 22:16 where God swears by Himself to Abraham. As the author of Hebrews observes (6:13-14), when God swears by Himself, the oath is absolute — there is no higher guarantor, no possible non-fulfillment. Amos uses this formula not for a promise of blessing but for a decree of judgment. God declares that He 'loathes' (taav) the arrogance of Jacob and 'detests' (sane) his citadels. Both verbs are in the strongest register of Hebrew moral aversion. What Jacob considers his pride (gaon) — the same word used for God's own majesty in Exodus 15:7 — God considers loathsome precisely because Israel has appropriated divine honor for itself. The oath transforms the oracle from prophetic warning into irreversible divine decree. Amos 3:7 established that God reveals His counsel to His servants the prophets; 6:8 reveals that counsel in the form of an unbreakable oath."
