          "title": "The horror scene — silence where the LORD's name cannot be spoken",
          "body": "Verses 9-11 shift the rhetorical register from oracle to narrative vignette, and the effect is chilling. Ten men in one house — all dead (6:9). A relative comes to collect the remains; he finds one survivor hidden in the innermost part of the house and asks, 'Is anyone else with you?' 'No one' (6:10). Then the command: 'Keep quiet. For the name of the LORD is not to be mentioned.' Commentators have debated whether this silence reflects terror of further divine wrath (invoking the name might summon more judgment) or despair so total that prayer seems impossible. Both readings are consistent with the context and both are theologically coherent. What Amos establishes is the absolute thoroughness of God's command (6:11): the great house smashed to pieces, the small house to fragments. No economic class, no sized dwelling escapes. The vignette does what the oracle cannot do alone: it forces the reader to stand in that house, to smell that scene, to hear that silence. The feasting of 6:4-6 and the horror of 6:9-11 are deliberately juxtaposed — the banquet hall becomes the charnel house."
