          "title": "The absurdity argument and the foreign nation — justice perverted and sovereignty asserted",
          "body": "The chapter's final movement (6:12-14) closes with a two-part argument that answers the self-congratulation of Israel's military class (6:13). The rhetorical questions of 6:12 — 'Do horses run on rocks? Does one plow them with oxen?' — appeal to observable nature: certain actions are impossible because they violate the order of creation. Then Amos delivers the punch: 'Yet you have turned justice (mishpat) into poison and the fruit of righteousness (tsedaqah) into wormwood.' Corrupting justice is as categorically absurd as equine rock-racing; it is a violation of the moral order as surely as the other is a violation of the natural order. Douglas Stuart (Word Biblical Commentary) notes that mishpat and tsedaqah are the twin pillars of covenant social life throughout the prophets (cf. Amos 5:24; Isaiah 5:7; Micah 6:8); their corruption signals not merely individual sin but the collapse of the covenant community's entire reason for existence. The final verse (6:14) answers the boasting of 6:13 with sovereign precision: you rejoice in Lo-debar (nothing) and Karnaim (strength); I am raising a nation that will afflict you from your northern border to your southern border — the full extent of the territory you just celebrated. God's answer to human boasting is not argument but history."
