        "title": "Woe to the complacent elite — ease as covenant betrayal",
        "range": "6:1-3",
        "excerpt": "Woe to those who are at ease in Zion and to those who feel secure in the mountain of Samaria, the distinguished men of the foremost of nations, to whom the house of Israel comes.",
        "body": "The opening 'Woe' (hoy) is not a wish but a pronouncement — the Hebrew funeral cry repurposed by the prophets to announce that the mourning process has begun in the divine council over those who do not yet know they are dying. Amos directs it simultaneously at Zion (Jerusalem) and Samaria — both capitals, both ruling classes. This dual address is significant: the prophet's primary audience is the northern kingdom, but he refuses to let Judah exempt itself from the indictment. The sin of covenant privilege carelessly held is not a northern-only disease.\n\nThe men indicted are 'the distinguished ones of the foremost of nations, to whom the house of Israel comes' (6:1). These are not marginal figures — they are the ones Israel itself recognizes as leaders, the ones people bring their grievances to, the ones who shape the moral and legal culture. Their position of privilege is precisely what makes their complacency so catastrophic. Luke 12:48 will later state the principle explicitly: 'to whom much is given, much is required.' Amos is operating in the same moral logic centuries earlier.\n\nThe commanded tour of 6:2 is the chapter's first argument. Calneh, Hamath, and Gath are chosen because they were significant — great by ancient Near Eastern standards — and yet they had fallen or been diminished before the Assyrian advance. Paul Garnet and other commentators note that the question 'Are they better than these kingdoms?' expects a negative answer: No, they were not better, and they fell anyway. The argument is simple: historical precedent destroys the logic of immunity. Israel's elite have constructed a theology of election that functions as insurance against judgment; Amos dismantles it by pointing at ruins.\n\nVerse 3 identifies the psychological mechanism of complacency: the active suppression of prophetic warning. 'You put off the day of calamity' — the verb nada implies pushing something away, distancing it. But simultaneously 'you bring near the seat of violence' — their own economic injustice, judicial corruption, and social callousness are in fact accelerating the judgment they are trying to push away. The tragic irony of self-protective denial is that the denial itself is part of the sin that generates the judgment.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Shaanan* (at ease, 6:1) — careless tranquility, also used in Isaiah 32:9,11 for women who should be alarmed. *Batach* (secure, 6:1) — the same root used for righteous trust in God (Psalm 4:5); here it describes misplaced confidence in Samaria's fortification. *Nada* (put off, 6:3) — to push away, repel. *Shevet chamas* (seat of violence) — the throne or rule of violent injustice."
