        "title": "The anatomy of indifference — luxury without grief",
        "range": "6:4-7",
        "excerpt": "Those who recline on beds of ivory and sprawl on their couches... yet they have not grieved over the ruin of Joseph. Therefore, they will now go into exile at the head of the exiles.",
        "body": "The extended portrait of vv. 4-6 is the most detailed account of elite excess in the pre-exilic prophets. Amos is no aesthetic ascetic condemning pleasure as such; his specific moral target is named only at the very end of the list — 'they have not grieved over the ruin of Joseph' (6:6). Everything before that is the setup: the ivory beds, the choice cuts of meat, the musical improvisation, the wine in sacrificial bowls, the finest oils. The list establishes the level of insulation. Only then does the prophetic indictment land: you have constructed a life so cushioned from consequence that the fracturing (shever) of the covenant community around you does not penetrate.\n\nThe ivory beds deserve special attention. Archaeological excavations at Samaria in 1931-1935 unearthed more than five hundred fragments of carved ivory panels consistent with bed-inlays and furniture decoration, now housed in the British Museum and the Rockefeller Museum in Jerusalem. Amos is not using rhetorical hyperbole; he is describing objects that existed, that his audience owned. The material culture of eighth-century Samaria confirms the prophet's social analysis.\n\nThe reference to music 'like David' (6:5) is particularly sharp. David composed music for the worship of God — the Psalms are his legacy. These men improvise music for their own entertainment, appropriating the Davidic vocabulary of artistry while emptying it of its theocentric content. The comparison is self-flattering and simultaneously self-condemning. Calvin observes that the imitation of David's form without David's heart is one of the most damning patterns in Israel's religious history — liturgical expertise combined with moral bankruptcy.\n\nThe sentence of 6:7 is a masterwork of lex talionis precision. 'Therefore, they will now go into exile at the head of the exiles' — the Hebrew *rosh haggolim*, 'head of the exiles.' Those first in feasting will be first in exile. The same position of prominence that defined their luxury now defines their punishment. And 'the sprawlers' banqueting (mirzach) will pass away.' The very institution — the marzeah, the ritual feast or guild-banquet known from extrabiblical texts at Ugarit and later at Elephantine — will cease to exist. The infrastructure of their insulation will be dismantled.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Sarach* (sprawl, lounge, 6:4, 7) — to spread out, to overflow, a word with connotations of excess and laxity. *Shever yoseph* (ruin of Joseph, 6:6) — shever is a breaking or fracture, used of the breaking of bones (Leviticus 24:20) and the breaking of a people (Isaiah 1:28). *Mirzach* (banqueting/feasting, 6:7) — the marzeah, a social institution of communal feasting known from Ugaritic texts as early as the 14th century BC, sometimes associated with funerary rites."
