        "number": 4,
        "title": "Justice perverted and sovereignty asserted — the closing argument",
        "range": "6:12-14",
        "excerpt": "Yet you have turned justice into poison and the fruit of righteousness into wormwood... 'For behold, I am going to raise up a nation against you, O house of Israel.'",
        "body": "The chapter's closing movement begins with two rhetorical questions that invoke natural law: 'Do horses run on rocks? Or does one plow them with oxen?' The expected answer is obviously no — both would destroy the instrument (the horse's hooves, the oxen's plows). Both are violations of the natural order, absurd on their face. Then comes the adversative pivot: 'Yet you have turned justice (mishpat) into poison and the fruit of righteousness (tsedaqah) into wormwood.' The structure makes the point inescapable: perverting justice is as categorically absurd as equine rock-racing, as self-destructive as plowing stone. You are destroying the instrument — the covenant social order — that makes your community possible.\n\nMishpat and tsedaqah are the twin pillars of prophetic social ethics throughout the Old Testament. Amos has already invoked them in their positive form ('let justice roll down like waters and righteousness like an ever-flowing stream,' 5:24). Here he names their inversion. 'Poison' (rosh, also used for hemlock or some toxic plant) and 'wormwood' (laanah, a bitter plant, Artemisia) both describe substances that appear like food or drink but kill. Justice has been weaponized against the vulnerable; what should nourish the community is instead poisoning it.\n\nVerse 13 names the specific occasion of Israel's boasting: military victories at Lo-debar and Karnaim, likely associated with Jeroboam II's northern expansion described in 2 Kings 14:25-28. Amos exploits the Hebrew wordplay with surgical precision. Lo-debar (lodevar) means 'nothing' or 'no-word' — Israel is rejoicing over a conquest of nothing. Karnaim means 'two horns' (symbols of strength and power) — Israel attributes its military horn to its own chozeq (strength). The prophet is not merely mocking their pride; he is identifying the specific theological error: the attribution of God-given military success to human strength, which is the same gaon-error of 6:8 applied to foreign policy.\n\nThe chapter closes with the most concrete threat of the entire oracle. 'Behold, I am going to raise up a nation against you' (6:14). The Assyrian empire — Tiglath-Pileser III in 745-727 BC, Shalmaneser V and then Sargon II who destroyed Samaria in 722/721 BC — is the referent, though Amos does not name it. The geographic precision 'from the entrance of Hamath to the brook of the Arabah' maps the full extent of the northern kingdom under Jeroboam II's expansion. The territory that was the evidence of God's blessing (2 Kings 14:26-27, where God restored the border out of compassion for Israel's misery) will now become the map of their affliction. The very borders of their pride become the borders of their occupation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Mishpat* (justice, 6:12) — covenant legal order, the right ordering of society. *Tsedaqah* (righteousness, 6:12) — conformity to covenant relational standards, often expressed in protection of the vulnerable. *Rosh* (poison, 6:12) — a bitter or toxic substance, possibly hemlock; same word used in Deuteronomy 29:18 and Jeremiah 9:15. *Laanah* (wormwood, 6:12) — Artemisia, notoriously bitter; used in Proverbs 5:4 and Revelation 8:11 for catastrophic bitterness. *Chozeq* (strength, 6:13) — military prowess, the human arm."
